^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|This hand is a great illustration of why 2 over 1 is better than SAYC. Once duffer opens 1 spade, roberta loves her hand. Let's count roberta's Bergen Points after 1S. She has 12 HCP, two length, one quality suit, minus one for Qx for a total of 14 Starting Points. After, one spade bid, she can count 16 Dummy Points by adding two for the two doubletons. Therefore, if pard has 16+, slam is possible.|
PG| ***** 39 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|Unfortunately, in SAYC 2H is not a game force. Therefore, playing SAYC over 3D, roberta has to bid 4S to make sure they get to game. In 2 over 1, roberta can bid 3S, which is a slam try. With a weakish game forcing hand, she would bid 4S. So basically, it is much more difficult to bid slams using SAYC when both partners have 17ish point hands. In this particular hand, slam is so-so. There is a club loser for sure. And even if spades break 3-2, it is hard to come to 12 tricks. |
PG| ***** 40 ***** |


NT||cp|8|AT|
^B@2^*Bhondo717: ^*N|cp||at|The best bet (for slam) is to try and set up hearts, which requires 3-3 break. So, game is best. Assuming spades break, duffer can count five spades, one club after the lead, and three diamonds and one heart with a club ruff, gets to 11. But with bad spade break, back down to 10.  Now, because the Jack of diamonds is third, duffer can make 11 tricks. So after the first trick, I think the best line of play is win club, ruff club, draw trumps, and lose a spade. There is no reason to lose a heart.|
PG| ***** 41 ***** |


